    "body" : "<p>Another alternative to <code>System.arraycopy</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] stringArray = Arrays.copyOf(objectArray, objectArray.length, String[].class);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 19067,
      "reputation" : 5289,
      "user_id" : 44355,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/WZ3p5.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "david a.",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/44355/david-a"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1245427911,
    "creation_date" : 1245427911,
    "answer_id" : 1018802,
    "question_id" : 1018750,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>If you want to get a String representation of the objects in your array, then yes, there is no other way to do it.</p>\n\n<p>If you know your Object array contains Strings only, you may also do (instread of calling toString()): </p>\n\n<pre><code>for (int i=0;i&lt;String_Array.length;i++) String_Array[i]= (String) Object_Array[i];\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The only case when you could use the cast to String[] of the Object_Array would be if the array it references would actually be defined as String[] , e.g. this would work:</p>\n\n<pre><code>    Object[] o = new String[10];\n    String[] s = (String[]) o;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
